This species can be distinguished from other Palaearctic species by the long gonocoxites (more than half total length of male genitalia, 
Fig. 103
), almost completely dark yellow abdomen (tergite 7 and posterior half of tergite 6, brown, 
Fig. 16
) and scutum evenly covered with small setae. It is the only species with long gonocoxites that has the gonocoxite both smoothly curved (not strongly bent as in 

L. talyshensis
,

Fig. 121
) and without a triangular protrusion mediobasally (
Fig. 103
).
